title: For Sale:  Springfield 1903 National Match .30-06
postcontent: This is a National Match 1903 made by Springfield Armory (the government one) back in 1920.  These were issued and sold to participants (yes, the government sold guns directly to the public) of the Camp Perry matches back in the '20s and '30s.  What makes this a NM?  First it has a numbered bolt marked N.S. for nickeled steel.  Secondly, it has a serrated, target trigger; and a fine cross-etched NM butt plate w/trap.  The top handguard is stamped with the NM stock # D28179.  The rear sight is marked to 2800 yards, with the extra (NM) notch on top to take you to 3000 yrds.  The barrel has a star-gauged mark at the six-oclock on the muzzle, and is dated "SA 2-38".  The muzzle and throat wear measure near "0", making this an almost new (little shot) barrel.  The stock cartoughes indicate that SA has rebuilt this at least once (thus the new barrel).

The Star Model PD is a compact and lightweight semi-automatic pistol. The Model PD can be loaded with six .45 ACP pistol cartridges in the detachable internal magazine, plus one in the chamber, and was very popular with police and civilian users in the self-defense and backup gun role, especially in the United States.The Star PD improved on its predecessor (Star Model PKM) by using a low-profile adjustable rear sight and by removing material from the slide and other small changes. These modifications, combined with its aluminum alloy construction, resulted in a slim, compact, lightweight and relatively powerful pistol, revolutionary for the time. As it also bore an external resemblance to the well-known M1911 pistol, the gun sold very well in the U.S. This pistol began the trend towards the production by other manufacturers of compact 1911-style pistols, which continues to the present day.
